Here's the thing though - they're not wrong. In every campaign there are inaccuracies on both sides.  It's impossible to get everything 100% correct over a campaign cycle.  Even when you campaign with honest and noble intentions, mistakes happen. Facts and figures can be interpreted one way or another, and even accurate statements can be interpreted as lies under the right circumstances. Now add a 24x7 news cycle, pundits, podcasts, twitter, Facebook and everyone on the planet sharing their (usually dumbass) opinions all the time, yeah, it's really easy to get it in your head that everyone lies and there's no point in participating in government.  That, in a democracy, is simply not an option. Playing the "bOtH sIdEs tHe SaMe" card is lazy and counterproductive.  If you don't like either side, then it's your duty as a citizen to pick the side you like best, get involved, and work until you do like it. A democratic system of government was never designed for the citizenry to be hands off, but that's how we've come to treat it in the US.  So many people pay no attention and do nothing for 3.5 years, then moan and complain every general election cycle because they don't like the candidates or the party platform or whatever.
